{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_eustachy_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532531/1920071301/0335.xml":{"full_text":"Business N\news\nBusiness Outlook\nIn Middle West\nIs Believed Good\nprospects of Large Crop\nHelp Situation, Accord?\ning to Reports Gath?\nered by Manufacturers\nCrop ?T1?J? future business outlook r??\nfM,r'<! gathered from among the mem\nyrs of a national manufacturing asso?\nciation, most of whom are located in\nt-aiall towns throughout the Middle\nWest, are decidedly encouraging. The\n?eports are particularly interesting in\ntfcat th? majority of them comment\noC the fact that the small town re?\naler has had less need of reducing\nprices to stimulate business than have\nhis big cty brothers.\nThe crop outlook in Missouri, KafU\nsas, Iowa and Ohio is exceeding en?\ncouraging, and both retailers and manu?\nfacturers, in the small communities\nthroughout that section anticipate a\nfiir'y healthy trade, based on the prosr\npects of prosperity among the farmers.\nIn analyzing the reports, the secre?\ntan' of the association has taken into\nconsideration the transportation situ?\nation and arrived ?t the conclusion\nthat the farmers, by reason of the fact\nthat the shipping difficulties will make\nthe marketing of their crops a long\ndrawn out affair, are likely to be good\njpenders during a protracted period.\nWith money coming in at regular in?\ntervals, he believes that the farmer\nwill be inclined to string his purchases\nrut and thus buy more than he would\nif a quick market for his crops gave\nhim a large amount of spending money\nat one time.\nThe majority of manufacturers who\nreplied to the questionnaire anticipate\na late fall season in their products,\nvrfcich are of a seasonal character, be?\ncause of the general unsettled con?\nditions. They do not expect buying to\nbo as brisk at the start as it has been\nat the inauguration of seasons for the\npast two or three years, but they ex\n?pect it to develop in something like\nthe recent rushes for merchandise, be?\ncause of the long period during which\ntrailers have been almost wholly\nabsent from the wholesale markets.\nCommercial Credits\nHigh inventories are beinc frowned\nupon by bankers in financial state?\nments submitted by clients asking for\nr.ew loans or extensions of old ones.\nSeme of the inventories submitted by\ntextile merchants, according to a large\nbank catering to this trade, are run?\nning extremely high, due to the drop\nin sales which be<ran in February and\nwhich have been declining steadily\never since. In sales figures bankers\nalso are inquiring for reports on the\namount of merchandise sold as well\nas its monetary value.\nCommercial money and bankers ac?\nceptance rates yesterday were un?\nchanged. Bankers' acceptance rates\npublished by the American Acceptance\nCouncil were:\nMember Non-Member j\nBanks. Banks.\nBuy. Sell. Buy. Sell.\nThirty days 6\\l 5\"a 6% 6%\nSixty days 6^, 6 6V? 6*4\nNinety days 63's 6*4 6?? 6%\n\nStabilization in Silks\nTo Help Cotton Goods\nRelation of Two Drawn More\nClosely by Decline of\nFormer\nStabilization of either the silk or cot?\nton goods market, in the opinion of\nsome of the trade leaders, will lead\nto a settling of prices in the other.\nThe relation between the two has been\ndrawn more closely by the decline in\nsilk values, which will enable low\npriced silk fabrics to compete favor?\nably with some of the higher priced\ncottons.\nThe waist trade and also the dress\ntrade saw a switch from silks to cot?\nton when the former i cached such high\nprices. Cotton waists and dresses are\nfashionable this summer, as evidenced\nby the number of them being worn and\nby the large numbers that retailers are\nse.hng. With silks on a lower basis,\n?orne trade factors are looking for an\no'.ner turn in fashions. Several large\nciess goods jobbers are reported to be\nwaiting for some stabilization in the\nBilk market before making their com?\nmitments for future delivery of cot\ntens.\nWool Market Shaken\nFailure of African Company\nEmphasizes Situation\nCables from South Africa yesterday\nreported the failure of a large wool\ncompany in the Orange Free State and\nfocused mere attention on the local\nwool situation. With more woolen\nmills throughout the country suspend?\ning op-eratiuns or curtailing their pro\nauction to a few days a week, the wool\nmarket here has suffered a severe de\ncune.\nQuotations are little more than nom?\ninal and the stoppage in trading has\nreached back to the domestic wool\ngrowers who, in a large measure, have\n?rten J?nab?e to market this year's clip,\ni he Federal Reserve Bank is permit?\nting local banks in the wool-growing\ndistricts to advance small amounts on\nthe- wool crop. The large wool dealers\n?re refusing to accept wool on consign?\nment, and make advances to the grow?\ners against it. To further unsettle\nconditions the restrictions on the mar?\nketing of\" Australian wool, on which\nw?8 market depends to a great extent,\nnave been removed by the British Gov?\nernment, and a free auction is sched?\nuled for October. In the new wool\nmarket the belief is growing that fu\nprices will be determined largely\nM the Australian auctions.\n\nSilk Jobbers Coming\nThe silk market opened the week in\na Quiet manner. Manufacturers and\ncommission agents expect little busi\nn*?s this week, but anticipate more\nactivity next week with the arrival of\njobbing buyers for their convention.\n?r?e of the points that is receiving\ncareful attention is the possible pro\nPortion that buying for retail channels\nW1*l bear to the purchasing by gar?\nant manufacturers. During the last\ntwo or three years the garment mak?\ners have been taking less goods and the\nretail trades more. This was due to\nthe turning of demand from ready\nmade garments to piece goods to be\nmade up in the home or by a dress\nmktr. Some silk manufacturers esti?\nmate that fully 80 per cent of the silks\n?old during the past two years have\n?one into consumers' hands over the\nMUSI counter in yardage rather than\nthrough the medium of made-up gar?\nments. Whether this proportion will\nbe maintained in the future is a puz\n????ng question*\nNew Cotton ?Good? Out\n*n anticipation of the great number\ni dress goods buyers who will be here\nJ?xt week for the convention of dress\n?brie buyers, cotton goods converter?\nart?, opening their lines of new nu?\nterials tor spring, 1921. Much of the\nfuture trend of the cotton goods mar?\nket, as well as the silk and woolen\ngoods markets, depends on the action\nof the buyers when they arrive in the\nmarket. Some of the converters and\nother sellers of cotton goods say that\nthey have made their prices as low as\npossible in order to induce the jobbers,\nwho in turn supply the retailers, to op?\nerate now for next spring.\n\"i\nMaking Shoes for Fall\nMost of the country's shoe factories\nswung into fall production yesterday.\nReporta from the shoe manufacturing\ncenters of Brockton, Lynn, Rochester\nand Cincinnati indicate that the fac?\ntories there had resumed operations\nafter a lay-off period of one or two\nweeks. Brooklyn apparently is recover?\ning more slowly, and the Brooklyn\nmanufacturers are awaiting a revival\nof buying before beginning extensive\nproducing operations. This is ac?\ncounted for by the fact that Brooklyn\nmade shoes are largely highly styled\nand the retailers wait until styles aro\nmore settled before placing orders for\nthis class of footwear.\n.i.\nWorsted Mill Reopens\nLAWRENCE, Mass., July 12.?The\nUswoco Mills of the United States\nWorsted Company, employing 1,500\nhands, and Walworth Bros.' worsted\nmill, employing 300, were reopened to?\nday after a shutdown of two weeks.\n\nBusiness Troubles\nPetitions in Bankruptcy\nThe following petitions In bankruptcy\nwer? filed yesterday In the United States\nDistrict Court:\nJOE-S SHIPYARD HOTEL. INC.?In\nvolurrtary petition against Joe-S Shipyard\nHotel, Inc., Newburgh, N. Y. Statte! lia?\nbilities, $7,000; assets not given. Samuel\nC. Duberstein, 63 Park Row, attorney for\nthe three creditor? petitioning.\nALM ADO CONFECTIONS, INC.?Invol?\nuntary petition against Alroarto Confec?\ntions, Inc., manufacturers, 623 to 629\nEighth Avenue. Liabilities, $40,000; assets,\n816,000. Zalkln Cohen, 49 Chambers\nStreet, attorneys for the petitioning cred?\nitors.\nReceiver? In Bankruptcy\nThe following receiver in bankruptcy was\nappointed yesterday In the United States\nDistrict Court.\nJOE-S SHIPYARD HOTEL, INC\nJudge William I. Grubb appointed a re?\nceiver for the Joe-S Shipyard Hotel, Inc.,\nNewburgh. N. Y., with a bond of $1,600.\nLiabilities, $7,000; assets not stated.\nSchedules In Bankruptcy\nSchedules In bankruptcy filed yesterday\nIn the United States District Court were as\nfollows:\n,?V.OUIS MIDLER?Schedules of Louis\nMiller, Jobber In silks, 22 West Nineteenth\nStreet, show liabilities of $89.346 and\nassets of 878,328.\nJudgments\nIn New York County\nThe following judgments wore filed yes?\nterday, the first name being that of the\ndebtor:\nAtteridge. Harold and Harry Car?\nroll?D Lewis. 8783.29\nBartlett, Eliza?W W Foster et al 114.70\nBalfour, Elinor and John Far\nrelly?Anchor Post Iron Works 124.24\nCrowe, Aubrey C?S Brill et al.. 3 03.46\nCorvan, Robert?J N Ho?. 167.96\nCarroll. James?Hecht Co, Inc.. 157.90\nDe Cario, Michael, Joseph Florio,\nNito Trumille and Selvatore\nOasella?C R Rosenschein_ 1,031.70\nDalton, Wm A?T Malandre et al 244.20\nElo Blay Co?N Halperln et al.. 260.93\nEpstein. Rosalind or Rose?H\nBeitenstool 171.70\nEdelman, Henry (General Con?\ntracting Co)?M Jasphson.... 103.15\nEllery, Edw D?A Levine. 141.20\nFrledenthnl, Joseph L?M Davis. 6,143.55\nFrlchtenbaum, Louis?S Hoffman\n?et al 345.05\nFarrano, Patrick or Pat, and\nSamuel Lemberg?Jos Musllner\nCo, Inc. 273.94\nFaunce, John B?R Knoppert.... 668.49\nFleming, Edw K?3 Brill et al.. 116.10\nFalco, Eugene?Victory J Pent.. 102.89\nFinkel, Abraham?A Naidoff_ 1,364.90\nFinkel, Abraham and Julius Olf?\nA Naido